<TEXT>
an agriculture department survey shows that 
farmers intend to boost corn plantings this spring with easier 
federal curbs and higher market prices helping them bounce back 
from last years drought 
the survey announced on friday showed that farmers intend to 
plant 733 million acres to corn up 8 percent from last year 
soybean plantings are expected to rise 5 percent from 1988 to 617 
million acres 
officials said the report was based on an annual us survey of 
about 65000 farmers in early march increases from last year were 
also indicated for grain sorghum wheat including winter durum 
and other spring varieties tobacco dry edible beans and sweet 
potatoes 
farmers indicated they would plant fewer acres this year of 
oats hay cotton rice and peanuts 
if farmers follow through with their plans the corn acreage 
would be the most since 767 million acres were planted for the 
1986 crop in 1985 plantings reached 834 million acres 
the planted corn acreage dropped to 602 million acres in 1983 
another year of severe drought 
last year of the 676 million acres planted 581 million were 
harvested for grain yielding 492 billion bushels down 30 percent 
from the 1987 crop average yields dropped to 846 bushels per acre 
from a record of 1194 bushels in 1987 
there was no indication of 1988 production in the report winter 
wheat output will be indicated by the usda for the first time on 
may 11 and corn figures in august along with soybeans cotton and 
other springplanted crops 
total wheat plantings for this years harvest was indicated at 
743 million acres up by more than 13 percent from last year 
winter wheat was reported at 547 million acres up 12 per cent 
durum 386 million up 16 percent and other springplanted wheat 
157 million acres up 17 percent 
officials cautioned that the actual acreage planted by farmers 
this spring may vary from intentions because of the effects of 
weather availability of production inputs changes in market 
conditions prior to planting and the impact of the usda report 
itself 
with production cut by last years drought market prices of 
grains and soybeans rose sharply the usda also relaxed 
acreagereduction requirements under wheat and feed grains programs 
for 1989 
preliminary price figures for march showed on thursday that the 
average farm price of wheat was 416 per bushel up from 274 a 
year ago corn was reported at 261 against 186 in march 1988 
and soybeans were 757 per bushel compared with 605 a year 
earlier 
other crops included in the survey report 
cotton plantings 11 million acres down 12 percent from 1988 
sorghum 118 million acres up 14 percent 
barley 962 million acres down 1 percent 
oats 132 million acres down 5 percent 
hay 631 million acres down 4 percent 
rice 286 million acres down 2 percent 
peanuts 164 million acres down 1 percent 
tobacco 713000 acres up 13 percent 
dry edible beans 167 million acres up 11 percent 
sweet potatoes 94000 acres up 2 percent 
</TEXT>
