<TEXT>
soviet authorities have released hundreds of 
dissidents from confinement but at least 100 remain in prisons 
labor camps and psychiatric hospitals amnesty international 
reported 
the group released its latest soviet human rights report on 
friday two days after the world psychiatry associations executive 
committee voted to readmit a soviet organization 
many psychiatrists in that association were reported opposed to 
the decision which must be approved by its general assembly later 
this year however amnesty officials declined comment on that vote 
the human rights organization said it had asked to speak with 
soviet officials about the cases during the threeday visit of 
president mikhail s gorbachev to britain which begins wednesday 
they said they had received no response 
amnesty also said in its report that soviet citizens still could 
be prosecuted for exercising free speech or religion 
although there has been much improvement and discussion of 
human rights in the soviet union and the rhetoric of human rights 
will no doubt dominate next weeks visit the reality is that there 
are still serious human rights concerns there said marie 
staunton director of the groups british section 
she and the coordinator for soviet affairs mick venables spoke 
to reporters about amnesty internationals most recent briefing 
paper on soviet human rights dated march 1989 
it says amnesty international knows of at least 100 prisoners 
known or thought to be dissidents including 25 in psychiatric 
hospitals but that 300 have been freed since 1987 
although some prisoners have been transferred to better 
facilities since 1987 those still in labor camps and prisons are 
kept on monotonous meager rations with only rudimentary medical 
care and have to meet excessively high work targets often 
involving heavy physical labor the report said 
venables added there has been no major improvement in the 
condition of prisoners cruelty and degrading treatment still 
continues 
psychiatric patients are given unnecessary drugs a treatment 
meted out as a form of intimidation he said 
most of the 100 prisoners are people who tried to emigrate 
without permission or conscientious objectors to mandatory military 
service amnesty said it said others are held for violating laws 
that restrict freedom of expression religion assembly and 
association 
it welcomed elements of the new soviet criminal code that 
recognize international rights agreements abolish internal exile 
and reduce the number of capital crimes from 18 to six 
a delegation from amnesty is currently in the soviet union for a 
nineday visit that is scheduled to end sunday 
